# On-the-Fly Protocol

> When the system encounters a gap — a tool that doesn't exist, an agent capability that's missing — it does not stop. It builds what it needs, verifies it, registers it, and continues. This is the self-repair engine.

---

## Trigger Conditions

Zeus activates this protocol when any of the following are true:

| Condition | Example |
|---|---|
| A required tool is not in `tool-registry.mdc` | Task needs a DTO validator, none registered |
| An agent is asked to do something outside their domain | QA asked to write a deployment script |
| A task type has no defined quality gate in `quality-gates.md` | New task type encountered for the first time |
| An agent explicitly surfaces a capability gap | "I cannot do X — no tool exists for this" |

---

## Protocol Steps

### Step 1 — Identify
Zeus names the gap precisely.

```
GAP IDENTIFIED:
  Type:    [tool / agent capability / quality gate]
  Missing: [exact name and purpose of what's needed]
  Needed for: [current task context]
  Blocking: [what cannot proceed without this]
```

### Step 2 — Spec
Zeus writes a minimal, unambiguous spec before any building begins.

```
TOOL SPEC:
  Name:        [identifier — kebab-case]
  Type:        [skill / hook / command / subagent]
  Purpose:     [one sentence — what it does]
  Input:       [what it receives]
  Output:      [exactly what it produces]
  Constraints: [hard rules it must follow]
  Owner agent: [which agent uses this tool]
  Verify by:   [how to confirm it works]
```

> Zeus does not hand a vague spec to Builder. A vague spec produces a vague tool.

### Step 3 — Spawn Builder
Zeus delegates to Builder Agent with the complete spec.

```
Agent:       Builder
Task:        Create [tool name] per the attached spec
Input:       Spec above + context of current task
Constraints: Must be self-contained. Must include usage example. Must not depend on unregistered tools.
Output:      Complete tool file + ready-to-paste tool-registry.mdc entry
Gate:        Zeus reviews output against spec before accepting
```

### Step 4 — Verify
Zeus does not skip this step under any circumstance.

Verification checklist:
- [ ] Tool does exactly what the spec says — no more, no less
- [ ] Tool handles invalid or empty input without crashing
- [ ] Tool output matches the declared output contract
- [ ] Usage example runs correctly
- [ ] No dependencies on tools not in the registry

If verification fails → return to Builder with specific failure reason. Not "this is wrong." Exactly what criterion it failed.

### Step 5 — Register
Zeus adds the tool to `tool-registry.mdc` with status `draft`.

Status becomes `active` after the tool is used successfully on one real task.

### Step 6 — Invoke
Zeus uses the newly created tool immediately for the task that triggered the gap.

### Step 7 — Log
Zeus writes to `tasks/decisions.md`:

```
DECISION: Created [tool name]
Date:      [session date]
Reason:    [what gap it filled]
Spec:      [link or inline spec]
Outcome:   [did it work on first use?]
```

---

## Anti-Patterns (Never Do These)

| Anti-Pattern | Why It's Dangerous |
|---|---|
| Build a tool without a spec | Produces something that almost does what's needed — the worst kind of bug |
| Skip verification to save time | An unverified tool in production is a ticking failure |
| Use a tool before registering it | Next session, Zeus won't know it exists — gets rebuilt, duplicated |
| Build a tool that depends on another unregistered tool | Creates invisible dependency chains that break silently |
| Let an agent build their own tool without Zeus oversight | Agents optimize for their domain — Zeus optimizes for the system |

---

## Example: Full On-the-Fly Cycle

**Scenario:** Backend Agent needs to validate Spring Boot DTO coverage but no tool exists.

```
Step 1 — Identify:
  GAP: No tool for DTO validation coverage check
  Blocking: Backend output cannot be verified before QA gate

Step 2 — Spec:
  Name: validate-spring-dto
  Type: skill
  Purpose: Verify that all DTO fields have appropriate @Valid constraint annotations
  Input: DTO class file(s)
  Output: Report listing fields with constraints, fields missing constraints, pass/fail verdict
  Constraints: Java/Spring Boot only. Must not modify files — read-only analysis.
  Owner: Backend Agent, QA Agent
  Verify by: Run against a known DTO with intentional missing constraint — must flag it

Step 3 — Spawn Builder with above spec

Step 4 — Verify: Zeus runs against test DTO → missing constraint flagged correctly → PASS

Step 5 — Register in tool-registry.mdc (status: draft)

Step 6 — Invoke on current task

Step 7 — Log in tasks/decisions.md
```

After this cycle, `validate-spring-dto` is permanently available in the registry.
